<paragraph blockId="7.[151,1437,788,1391]" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,349,1004,1030]" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">Recognition.</emphasis>
Small greyish delicate flies (body length 
<quantity box="[809,922,1004,1031]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="3.25" metricValueMax="3.5" metricValueMin="3.0" pageId="7" pageNumber="8" unit="mm" value="3.25" valueMax="3.5" valueMin="3.0">3–3.5 mm</quantity>
) with very slender legs almost lacking distinct setae, eyes dichoptic in both sexes, separated by broad V-shaped flattened frons; legs black to reddish brown, “knees” often somewhat paler (
<figureCitation box="[414,486,1076,1102]" captionStart="FIGURES 2–5" captionStartId="8.[151,264,1640,1664]" captionTargetBox="[153,1435,183,1614]" captionTargetId="figure-20@8.[151,1437,181,1616]" captionTargetPageId="8" captionText="FIGURES 2–5. Brachystomatidae (2) and Empididae, Clinocerinae (3–5). 2. Heleodromia pullata (Melander), male habitus, lateral view; 3. Clinocera nivalis (Zetterstedt), male habitus, lateral view; 4. Trichoclinocera lapponica (Ringdahl), male habitus, lateral view; 5. same species, male postabdomen, lateral view." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4406991" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4406991/files/figure.png" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">Fig. 2</figureCitation>
). Male terminalia large, reniform; tergite 8 simple, lacking dorsomedial elongation or process (
<bibRefCitation author="Sinclair, B. J. &amp; Brooks, S. E. &amp; Cumming, J. M. &amp; Coovert, G. A." box="[285,568,1112,1139]" pageId="7" pageNumber="8" pagination="629 - 651" refId="ref65374" refString="Sinclair, B. J., Brooks, S. E., Cumming, J. M. &amp; Coovert, G. A. (2011) Revision of the Nearctic species of Heleodromia (Diptera: Empidoidea: Brachystomatidae). The Canadian Entomologist, 143, 629 - 651. https: // doi. org / 10.4039 / n 11 - 036" type="journal article" year="2011">
Sinclair 
<emphasis box="[383,435,1112,1138]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">et al</emphasis>
. 2011: 644
</bibRefCitation>
, fig. 11B); epandrial lobe slender, digitiform; surstylus slightly shorter than epandrial lobe, with apical third slender and digitiform; phallus with apex membranous and broad.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="7" pageNumber="8" type="distribution">
<paragraph blockId="7.[151,1437,788,1391]" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,353,1184,1210]" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">Distribution.</emphasis>
Holarctic; in North America, 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Melander" authorityYear="1902" box="[702,818,1184,1211]" class="Insecta" family="Empididae" genus="Sciodromia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="8" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="pullata">
<emphasis box="[702,722,1185,1210]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">H</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis box="[739,818,1184,1210]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">pullata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is widely distributed in northern 
<collectingCountry box="[1209,1293,1184,1210]" name="Canada" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">Canada</collectingCountry>
and Alaska, occurring on tundra and in boreal forests, with isolated populations in the Rocky Mountains of Arizona, Colorado and New Mexico (
<bibRefCitation author="Sinclair, B. J. &amp; Brooks, S. E. &amp; Cumming, J. M. &amp; Coovert, G. A." box="[357,573,1256,1283]" pageId="7" pageNumber="8" pagination="629 - 651" refId="ref65374" refString="Sinclair, B. J., Brooks, S. E., Cumming, J. M. &amp; Coovert, G. A. (2011) Revision of the Nearctic species of Heleodromia (Diptera: Empidoidea: Brachystomatidae). The Canadian Entomologist, 143, 629 - 651. https: // doi. org / 10.4039 / n 11 - 036" type="journal article" year="2011">
Sinclair 
<emphasis box="[452,500,1256,1282]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">et al</emphasis>
. 2011
</bibRefCitation>
); in Eurasia, it is known from Taymyr Peninsula and Magadanskaya Province of 
<collectingCountry box="[182,260,1292,1318]" name="Russia" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">Russia</collectingCountry>
. Among the Russian Arctic islands, 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Melander" authorityYear="1902" box="[664,777,1292,1319]" class="Insecta" family="Empididae" genus="Sciodromia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="8" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="pullata">
<emphasis box="[664,684,1293,1318]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">H</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis box="[698,777,1292,1318]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">pullata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is recorded only from Wrangel Island.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="7.[151,1437,788,1391]" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,298,1328,1354]" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">Habitat.</emphasis>
This species was collected on Wrangel Island mainly in river beds, where it was found in biotopes with different moisture levels (also on stones).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="7.[151,418,1472,1498]" box="[151,418,1472,1498]" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,418,1472,1498]" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">
Family 
<taxonomicName box="[247,418,1472,1498]" class="Insecta" family="Empididae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="8" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="family">EMPIDIDAE</taxonomicName>
</emphasis>
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
